{"action_ids":["2682","2674"],"summary":"Studies in both the Mediterranean Sea and the Indian Ocean found that prohibiting all fishing in a protected area resulted in a different fish community composition compared to fished areas (2682). In both regions, studies also found higher fish species richness and abundance in no-take marine protected areas, although some studies found similar levels to fished areas (2682). The effect on fish abundance can vary between species and groups in both the Indian Ocean and the Mediterranean (2682, 2674).

In terms of fish size, studies in both the Indian Ocean and the Mediterranean Sea have found that no-take protected areas host larger fish compared to fished areas (2682). Specifically in the Indian Ocean, a study on zoned marine protected areas found larger fish in the no-take zones compared to partially fished zones (2674). Another study in the Indian Ocean noted that the stock biomass of reef fish was highest in enforced protected areas that were closed to all fishing (2682).

A study in the Mediterranean Sea found a higher number of eggs from commercially targeted fish species within a non-fished reserve (2682), and also that commercial fish catch rates were highest closest to a no-take reserve (2682). In the Indian Ocean, one study observed higher fish grazing rates in non-fished areas (2682). Another study in the Indian Ocean found that most individuals of five tagged fish species stayed within a marine reserve zone closed to fishing over a nine-year period (2682).","query":"How does the effectiveness of no-take marine protected areas on fish communities differ between the Mediterranean Sea and the Indian Ocean?"}

